The Sand Beach traffic counter along the Park Loop Road is flagged for estimation. The traffic counter failed to record 22 days in the month of March (03/01/18-03/22/18). Total recorded counts for Sand Beach (03/23-03/31) were 2081. Since there are over three weeks missing, we are using the daily estimate from a representative month last year. An estimate of 125-135 vehicles per day would be reasonable looking at the first three months of last year's data. To estimate the total traffic count, we used 125 vehicles per day on average and multiply by 22 days (counter was out). A little math... 125 average number of vehicles per day X 22 days out = 2750 vehicles. We know for the 9 days the counter was in service there was a recorded 2081 vehicles. 2750 + 2081 = 4831 vehicles estimated in the month of March 2018. Since this is an estimated number, we generally round the number so it does not look so exact. The number entered into Sand Beach this month is 4800. Schoodic Peninsula traffic count is an estimate based on a 5-year average. The ITS traffic counter along the Schoodic Loop road was struck by lightening and has not collected data on that device for years. Acadia currently uses portable traffic counters for visitor use May thru October on the Schoodic Peninsula.

The Sand Beach traffic counter along the Park Loop Road is flagged for estimation. The traffic counter failed to record 19 days in the month of April (04/11/18-04/30/18). Total recorded counts for Sand Beach (04/01-04/11) were 2525. 
Since there are over two weeks missing, we are using the daily estimate from April 2017. To estimate the total traffic count, we used the 390 vehicles per day average (April 2017 data) and multiply by 19 days (counter was out). 
A little math... 390 average number of vehicles per day X 19 days out = 7410 vehicles. We know for the 11 days the counter was in service there was a recorded 2525 vehicles. 7410 + 2525 = 9935 vehicles estimated in the month of April 2018. Since this is an estimated number, we generally round the number so it does not look so exact. The number entered into Sand Beach this month is 9900.

A very impressive Thanksgiving snow storm created a park wide power failure from 3 AM on November 27th (Friday) to 1:45 AM on November 28th (Saturday). A number of state highways were closed as well as large portions of interstate 40 from the night of November 26th thru the morning of November 29. The two days, November 27 & 28, following Thanksgiving tend to be two of the busiest days of the year. But this year it was a bust.

Cottonwood Traffic Data. In bound lane traffic counter at cottonwood did not function properly for 10 ½ days, roughly corresponding to wet weather. Data input was estimated close to the five year average which resulted in a 6% drop under last year’s traffic in that area. However, the O/I data at the cottonwood visitor center showed a 7.9% increase over last year; the traffic data estimated in the opposite direction does not follow.  Conversely the outbound lane counter at cottonwood functioned for all but one in the month of November and shows a total daily traffic for the month at 11,018. The average daily total (ADT) for Lane 1 with missing data is 400 and 380 for lane two, a 20% difference. The missing data occurred on days where visitor traffic was lower and if the data were present would likely bring the ADT of both lanes closer to the 380. Based on this, revising the lane 1 traffic to an estimated 10200 is a conservative estimate and brings the traffic data in line with the O and I data at the visitor center.

Due to road conditions from snowfall late Saturday, December 23 and blowing and drifting snow and ice combined with the inability to snowplow, sand or otherwise maintain the roads, gates were closed on December 24 past the Beaver Meadows Visitor Center on US 36, past the Fall River Entrance on US 34, past the Wild Basin Entrance on the Wild Basin Road and at the Grand Lake Entrance on US 34.  These entrances experienced walk-in visitors during the closure. The park is estimating an average parkwide of 500 walk-in visitors daily. For December this is 8 days (Monday, Dec 24, through Mon, Dec 31) x 500/day = 4000 walk-ins, and this estimate is added to the Beaver Meadows Entrance December count.

•	For the time period in January that roads were not accessible by vehicles, the park is estimating an average parkwide of 200 walk-in visitors daily. For January this is 13 days (Tuesday, January 1, through Sunday, January 13) x 200/day = 2600 walk-ins, and this estimate is added to the Beaver Meadows Entrance January count.
